# Plan: Add "mistral-instruct-v3" Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3 uses a simple `[INST]`/`[/INST]` chat format that is distinct from the newer Ministral 3 format (which uses `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, `[TOOL_CALLS]`, `[ARGS]` markers). A new specialized handler is needed to support this older but still widely-used format. The handler will be simpler than existing ones — no tool call support, no PEG parser, just manual prompt construction with `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY`.

## File to Modify

- **`common/chat.cpp`** — the only file that needs changes

## Changes

### Step 1: Add the handler function `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3`

**Location:** Insert before `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (before line 1634). A good placement is right before the `common_chat_try_specialized_template` function, after the last existing handler (GigaChat v3, which ends around line 1632).

**Implementation:**

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
    const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
    const autoparser::generation_params & inputs)
{
    common_chat_params data;

    std::string prompt = "<s>";
    std::string system_message;

    // First pass: extract system message if present
    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        auto role = msg.value("role", "");
        if (role == "system") {
            system_message = msg.value("content", "");
            break;
        }
    }

    bool first_user = true;
    for (const auto & msg : inputs.messages) {
        auto role    = msg.value("role", "");
        auto content = msg.value("content", "");

        if (role == "system") {
            // System message handled by prepending to first user message
            continue;
        } else if (role == "user") {
            if (first_user && !system_message.empty()) {
                prompt += "[INST] " + system_message + "\n" + content + " [/INST]";
            } else {
                prompt += "[INST] " + content + " [/INST]";
            }
            first_user = false;
        } else if (role == "assistant") {
            prompt += content + "</s>";
        }
    }

    data.prompt = prompt;
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY;

    return data;
}
```

**Key design decisions:**
- **Manual prompt building** by iterating `inputs.messages` (as specified in requirements), unlike other handlers which use `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl`
- **System message** is prepended to the first user message with a `\n` separator (matching the Mistral v0.3 format spec)
- **`COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY`** — no PEG parser needed since this is a simple text-only format
- Uses `msg.value("role", "")` and `msg.value("content", "")` following existing patterns
- Multi-turn produces: `<s>[INST] {sys}\n{user1} [/INST]{asst1}</s>[INST] {user2} [/INST]`

### Step 2: Register the handler in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`

**Location:** Inside `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` (lines 1634-1691). Add a new detection block. A logical placement is **after the existing Ministral 3 detection** (after line 1644), since both deal with Mistral-family templates and the detection logic is complementary (presence vs. absence of `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`).

**Detection logic:**

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - uses [INST]/[/INST] markers without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Why this detection works:**
- `[INST]` and `[/INST]` are present in the Mistral v0.3 template source
- `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` is **absent** in v0.3 (it's only present in Ministral 3 / Mistral Small 3.2 templates), cleanly distinguishing from the existing handler
- This is checked after the Ministral 3 block, so the more specific handler takes priority

## What is NOT changed

- **`common/chat.h`** — no modifications needed; `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_CONTENT_ONLY` already exists
- **All existing handlers and detection logic** — no modifications, only additions

## Verification

1. **Build test:** Compile llama.cpp to verify the new code compiles without errors:
   ```
   cd build && cmake .. && make -j
   ```
2. **Grep verification:** Confirm the new function and detection logic are present:
   ```
   grep -n "mistral_instruct_v3" common/chat.cpp
   grep -n "Mistral Instruct v3" common/chat.cpp
   ```
3. **Logic check:** Verify the detection does not conflict with Ministral 3 by confirming:
   - Ministral 3 templates contain `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` → matched by existing handler first
   - Mistral v0.3 templates contain `[INST]`/`[/INST]` but NOT `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` → matched by new handler
4. **Run existing tests** to ensure no regressions:
   ```
   ctest --test-dir build -R chat
   ```

